2 PART I: Using rgdal and sp

Package installation and loading:

install.packages("rgdal")
install.packages("sp")
# We use RColorBrewer for creating color palettes:
install.packages("RColorBrewer") 
library(rgdal)
library(sp)
library(RColorBrewer)

2.1 Import the shapefile

The shapefile of the AR6 reference regions is available for download at the IPCC-Atlas GitHub repository.

Function readOGR from package rgdal reads shapefiles into the R environment. The R object that is obtained is a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame, this is a Spatial* class object from package sp.

AR6_WGI_referenceRegions <- readOGR("MyDir/AR6_WGI_referenceRegions.shp")
class(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions)
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

2.2 Load the R object

The *.rda object is also provided in the same link, thus, the Spatial object of the regions can be directly loaded into R as follows:

load("MyDir/AR6_WGI_referenceRegions.rda", verbose = TRUE)
AR6_WGI_referenceRegions <- as(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, "SpatialPolygons")
## Loading objects:
##   AR6_WGI_referenceRegions

We can simplify this object by converting it to a SpatialPolygons class object.

AR6_WGI_referenceRegions <- as(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, "SpatialPolygons")

Use function plot to visualize the regions:

plot(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions)

The R basic plotting functions allow adding layers to the plot. Here the region names and coastline are added. Shapefiles such as the Global coast lines or country boundaries are easily obtained from the Internet (e.g. https://www.naturalearthdata.com/downloads/).

coastLines <- greadOGR("MyDir/world_coastlines.shp")
plot(coastLines, col = "grey")
plot(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, add = TRUE)
text(x = coordinates(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions)[,1],
    y = coordinates(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions)[,2],
    labels = names(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions), cex = 0.6)

2.3 Selecting specific regions

A singe region:

newzealand <- AR6_WGI_referenceRegions["NZ"]
plot(newzealand)
plot(coastLines, col = "grey", add = TRUE)
text(x = coordinates(newzealand)[,1],
    y = coordinates(newzealand)[,2],
    labels = names(newzealand), cex = 1)

or several:

australasia <- AR6_WGI_referenceRegions[c("NZ", "SEA", "NAU", "CAU", "SAU")]

plot(australasia)
plot(coastLines, col = "grey", add = TRUE)
text(x = coordinates(australasia)[,1],
    y = coordinates(australasia)[,2],
    labels = names(australasia), cex = 1)

2.4 Data loading

With the aim of illustrating how to work with the regions and gridded data, here we use as example the 1 degree IPCC Atlas reference land-sea mask, which is also available at GitHub in the form of a NetCDF file.

In this case, function readGDAL (package rgdal) is used:

grid1 <- readGDAL("MyDir/land_sea_mask_1degree.nc4")

The class of object grid1 is SpatialGridDataFrame from package sp:

class(grid1)
## [1] "SpatialGridDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

2.5 Visualization

Function spplot is the map plotting tool of package sp:

spplot(grid1, sp.layout = list(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, first = FALSE, col = "red", lwd = 2))

Argument sp.layout allows the visualization of as many Spatial* objects as we want. For example, region names can also be a Spatial object (object regnameslayer in the next example):

regnameslayer <- list("sp.text", coordinates(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions), names(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions), col = "red", cex = 0.6)
spplot(grid1, sp.layout = list(list(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, first = FALSE, col = "red", lwd = 2), regnameslayer))

Note that graphical parameters are easily set (e.g. col, cex, etc.)

2.6 Overlaping data and regions

The over function performs the instersection between different Spatial* object convinations, e.g.it implements the intersection of a SpatialPixelsDataFrame and a SpatialPolygons object. Therefore, next we convert grid1 to a SpatialPixelsDataFrame object:

grid1 <- as(grid1, "SpatialPixelsDataFrame")

The only requirement is equal projections. Use function proj4string to check and/or define, and spTransform to change the projection of a Spatial* object.

proj4string((AR6_WGI_referenceRegions))
## [1] "+init=epsg:4326 +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0"
proj4string((grid1))
## [1] NA

In this example we do know that the projection is WGS84, same as AR6_WGI_referenceRegions (EPSG:4326), thus:

proj4string(grid1) <- proj4string(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions)

Next over is applied for the regional subsets defined above:

mask.nz <- grid1[!is.na(over(grid1, newzealand)),]
mask.au <- grid1[!is.na(over(grid1, australasia)),]

We will keep the Austral-Asia subset from now on.

Note that spplot uses function levelplot internally (from the powerful lattice package (Sarkar, 2008) and therefore, fine-tuning plotting parameters from levelplot can be passed to spplot, for instance the color palette, here created with brewerPal (package RColorBrewer):

colpal <- rev(brewer.pal(9, "BrBG"))
cols <- colorRampPalette(colpal)(10)

aulayer <- list(australasia, first = FALSE, col = "red", lwd = 2)
aunameslayer <- list("sp.text", coordinates(australasia), names(australasia), col = "red")

spplot(mask.au, sp.layout = list(list(coastLines), aulayer, aunameslayer), 
       at = seq(0, 1, 0.1), col.regions = cols)

2.7 Data operations

For instance, the regional mean:

mean(mask.au@data$band1)
## [1] 0.3872107

2.8 Data filtering

For instance, retain values above 0.5:

mask.au <- mask.au[mask.au@data$band1 > 0.5,]
spplot(mask.au, sp.layout = list(list(coastLines), aulayer, regnameslayer), 
       at = seq(0, 1, 0.1), col.regions = cols)

The regional mean in this case is closer to 1 as it is calculated for the land area:

mean(mask.au@data$band1)
## [1] 0.9735857

3 PART II: Using climate4R

Package installation and loading:

library(devtools)
install_github(c("SantanderMetGroup/loadeR",
  "SantanderMetGroup/loadeR.java",
  "SantanderMetGroup/transformeR",
  "SantanderMetGroup/visualizeR",
  "SantanderMetGroup/geoprocessoR")

Note that there are more packages in climate4R. Here we use the ones required for this simple example. Go to the climate4R GitHub repository for more information and worked examples.

library(loadeR)
library(transformeR)
library(visualizeR)
library(geoprocessoR)

3.1 Load the AR6 regions

The Spatial* object of the regions is available in the visualizeR package, therefore, there is no need for previous download:

data("AR6_WGI_referenceRegions")

3.2 Data loading

Previous to download we can perform an inventory of the dataset.

di <- dataInventory("MyDir/land_sea_mask_1degree.nc4")
str(di)

As we can see from the inventory output it contains a single variable, this is sftlf (land/sea fraction). To load this data loadGridData is used:

grid1 <- loadGridData("MyDir/land_sea_mask_1degree.nc4", var = "sftlf")

3.3 Visualization

spatialPlot is the map plotting function in climate4R (package visualizeR), which uses spplot internally, so it works in a very similar way and implements additional useful parameters (backdrop.theme, set.min, set.max, lonCenter, color.theme, rev.colors).

spatialPlot(grid1, backdrop.theme = "coastline", 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            sp.layout = list(list(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions, first = FALSE, col = "blue"), regnameslayer))

3.4 Overlaping data and regions

Function overGrid perfoms the operation of intersecting a climate4R grid and a Spatial object. The only requirement is equal projections. Use function projectGrid to define and/or change the projection of a grid. Use proj4string and spTransform for Spatial objects. In this example we do know that the projection is WGS84 (EPSG:4326), thus:

grid1 <- projectGrid(grid1, original.CRS = proj4string(AR6_WGI_referenceRegions))
grid1.au <- overGrid(grid1, australasia)
spatialPlot(grid1.au, 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            sp.layout = list(coastLines, first = FALSE, col = "black"))

If we set argument subset as TRUE we obtain

grid1.au <- overGrid(grid1, australasia, subset = TRUE)

spatialPlot(grid1.au, 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            sp.layout = list(coastLines, first = FALSE, col = "black"))

3.5 Data operations

For instance, the regional mean:

mean(grid1.au$Data, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.3872107

It is convenient to use function aggregateGrid for data operations implying the aggregation of any of the dimensions, so that there is no need to extract the $Data and the grid object structure is mantained. Next we repeat the regional mean calculation but considering latitude weighting (weight.by.lat = TRUE):

regmean <- aggregateGrid(grid1.au, aggr.lat = list(FUN = "mean", na.rm = TRUE),
                         weight.by.lat = TRUE,
                         aggr.lon = list(FUN = "mean", na.rm = TRUE))
regmean$Data
## [1] 0.3400356
## attr(,"dimensions")
## [1] "time"

Other usefule function is gridArithmetics, to perfom arithmetic operations with climate4R grids. For instance:

grid100.au <- gridArithmetics(grid1.au, 100, operator = "*")
spatialPlot(grid100.au, 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            sp.layout = list(coastLines, first = FALSE, col = "black"))

3.6 Data filtering

Retain values above 0.5:

grid1.au$Data[which(grid1.au$Data <= 0.5)] <- NA

spatialPlot(grid1.au, 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            at = seq(0, 1, 0.1),
            sp.layout = list(coastLines, first = FALSE, col = "black"))

If we consider that >0.5 is land, we could create a land/sea mask applying this threshold (function binaryGrid), and apply it to the data (could be any variable) by using gridArithmetics:

land1.au <- binaryGrid(grid1.au, condition = "LE", threshold = 0.5, values = c(1, NA))
land1.au <- gridArithmetics(land1.au, grid1.au, operator = "*")

spatialPlot(land1.au, 
            color.theme = "BrBG",
            rev.colors = TRUE,
            at = seq(0, 1, 0.1),
            sp.layout = list(coastLines, first = FALSE, col = "black"))
